  1. Use the albersusa package to make a base map of the lower 48 US states.
us_comp <- usa_sf()
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = us_comp, size = 0.125) + 
  theme_linedraw()+
  labs(title = "USA Lower 48")

  1. Use the relimited data to plot the distribution of wolf populations in the lower 48 US states.
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = us_comp, size = 0.125) + 
  geom_point(data = wolves_lower_48,aes(long,lat,color=pop),size=2.5)+
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  labs(title = "Wolf Populations in the Lower 48 States (USA)",x="Longitude",y="Latitude")

  1. What is the average pack size for the wolves in this study by region?
names(wolves_lower_48)
##  [1] "pop"                "year"               "age_cat"           
##  [4] "sex"                "color"              "lat"               
##  [7] "long"               "habitat"            "human"

wolves_lower_48 %>% 
  group_by(pop) %>% 
  summarize(mean_packsize= mean(pack_size)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(mean_packsize))

  1. Make a new map that shows the distribution of wolves in the lower 48 US states but which has the size of location markers adjusted by pack size.
wolves_lower_48_new<-wolves_lower_48%>%
  group_by(pop)%>%
  mutate(mean_packsize=mean(pack_size))
head(wolves_lower_48_new)
